g.text: - RegionMap: is the name of the mapping.
- us-east-1 and us-west-1: are the regions
- Each region has an AMI ID (the machine image to launch EC2 instances)
A Mapping in CloudFormation is like a table or dictionary that stores key-value pairs. It's useful when you want to set different values based on
specific conditions like region or environment. (like if else condition)
If you are deploying resources in different AWS regions or environments (like production and development), you might need different settings
(such as different AMI IDs, instance types, etc.). Instead of hardcoding them, you can use a Mapping to store those values and refer to them
!FindInMap [RegionMap, !Ref 'AWS::Region', AMI]: This looks at the RegionMap, finds the current region
(AWS::Region), and returns the correct AMI for that region.
* To use the values from the Mappings section, you use the Fn::FindInMap intrinsic function
